# Allow systemd to create the nix-daemon listening socket.
#
# The Nix store lives on /var (the /var/nix btrfs subvolume) and is bind-mounted
# onto /nix at boot -- so every path under /nix is labeled default_t, and this
# image ships no Nix SELinux policy (no nix_* types, no fcontext, and the Fedora
# nix-core/nix-daemon RPMs ship none). nix-daemon is socket-activated, so systemd
# (init_t) must create the listening socket at /nix/var/nix/daemon-socket/socket.
# Under enforcing SELinux init_t may not create a sock_file in a default_t
# directory, so the socket unit fails with "Permission denied" and Nix is
# unusable. See docs/adrs/0016-nix-store-on-immutable-host.md.
#
# `unlink` is also required: the socket lives on the persistent /var/nix
# subvolume (bind-mounted onto /nix), so the socket file survives reboots
# (nix-daemon.socket does not set RemoveOnStop). On every boot after the first,
# systemd must unlink the leftover socket before rebinding; without this the
# unit fails "Failed to create listening socket" and `nix` reports the daemon
# socket "Connection refused". First boot works because the freshly seeded store
# has no socket file yet -- the failure only surfaces on the second and later
# boots.
#
# These rules were derived from the observed AVCs (create, write, unlink) and
# confirmed to make `nix run nixpkgs#hello` work under enforcing across reboots.
# They are intentionally scoped to exactly these permissions; unrelated denials
# (e.g. bootupd_t) are excluded.
module nix-daemon-socket 1.0;

require {
    type init_t;
    type default_t;
    class sock_file { create write unlink };
}

allow init_t default_t:sock_file { create write unlink };
